<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-logs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title><m>\ln</m> in Integration</title>

  <claim xml:id="claim-logs">
    <statement>
      <p>
        <me>\int_1^x \frac{1}{t}dt = \ln(x)</me>
        Where <m>\ln :\mathbb{R}^+\rightarrow\mathbb{R}</m> is the unique two-sided inverse of the bijective 
        <m>\exp :\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^+</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </claim>
  <proof>
    <p>
      <alert>Right inverse:</alert>
      let <m>f(x)=\int_1^x \frac{1}{t}dt</m> and <m>g(x) = e^{f(x)}</m>.
      Then 
      <md>
        <mrow>\implies g'(x) =\amp f'(x)e^{f(x)}</mrow>
        <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{x}e^{f(x)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\implies g''(x)=\amp f''(x)e^{f(x)} + f'(x)^2e^{f(x)}</mrow>
        <mrow> =\amp -\frac{1}{x^2}e^{f(x)} + \frac{1}{x^2}e^{f(x)}</mrow>
        <mrow> =\amp 0</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>g''(x) = 0</m> implies that <m>g'(x) = A</m> for some constant <m>A\in\mathbb{R}</m>.
      Thus, we have
      <me>g'(x) = g'(1) = \frac{1}{1}e^{f(1)} = 1.</me>
      Which in turn implies that <m>g(x)=x+c</m> for some constant <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m>. 
      Evaluated at <m>x=1</m>, we have
      <me>
        g(1) = e^f(1) = 1 = 1 + c
      </me>
      Thus, <m>c=0</m> and we have that 
      <me>
        g = \text{id}
      </me>
      as required.
    </p>
  </proof>
  

</section>